You’re pointing at a classic philosophical distinction: meaning vs. existence.

The object exists, but the meaning we attach to it is a layer we construct.

⸻

The Venus example

Venus is a good illustration.

For humans historically it appeared as two different objects:
	•	the Morning Star
	•	the Evening Star

Later astronomers realized they were the same planet.

The key insight is that the labels and meanings came from human interpretation, not from the planet itself.

Venus does not “know” it is:
	•	a goddess symbol
	•	a navigational reference
	•	a cultural omen

Those meanings exist in our cognitive and cultural systems.

⸻

Ontology vs interpretation

Philosophers often distinguish between:

level	meaning
ontology	what actually exists
epistemology	how we know things
semantics	what things mean

A rock, star, or planet exists independently of our stories about it.

But our understanding of it is mediated through:
	•	language
	•	models
	•	cultural narratives

⸻

The Morning Star paradox

This idea became famous in philosophy because of a puzzle noted by the philosopher Gottlob Frege.

The statements
	•	“The Morning Star is Venus”
	•	“The Evening Star is Venus”

contain different meanings even though they refer to the same object.

So meaning depends on the path of discovery, not just the object.

